.TH minibwa 1 "12 April 2026" "minibwa-0.0 (r234)" "Bioinformatics tools"
.SH NAME
.PP
minibwa - short/long-read alignment against a reference genome
.SH SYNOPSIS
* Indexing a genome with the libsais algorithm (OpenMP required for multi-threading):
.RS 4
minibwa index
.RB [ -t
.IR nThreads ]
.I ref.fa
.I idxPrefix
.RE

* Indexing a genome in low memory with the BWT-SW algorithm:
.RS 4
minibwa index
.B -l
.I ref.fa
.I idxPrefix
.RE

* Aligning short paired-end reads to an indexed genome and outputting SAM:
.RS 4
minibwa map
.B -a
.RB [ -t
.IR nThreads ]
.I idxPrefix
.I read1.fq.gz
.I read2.fq.gz
>
.I output.sam
.RE

.SH DESCRIPTION
Minibwa aligns short reads against a reference genome. It is the successor of
bwa-mem with a different algorithm. Minibwa is 3-4 times as fast as the
original bwa-mem and twice as fast as bwa-mem2 at comparable accuracy. While
minibwa works with accurate long reads, minimap2 is more robust.

Minibwa is named after bwa-mem and minimap2 and is based on the source code of
both projects: it indexes the genome with Burrow-Wheeler Transform (BWT), finds
variable-length seeds as nested SuperMaximal Exact Matches (SMEMs) like
bwa-mem, and performs chaining and SIMD-based nucleotide alignment with the
minimap2 algorithm. Minibwa speeds up bwa-mem2 further with effective prefetch
for seeding, additional heuristics to skip unnecessary mate rescue and reduced
effort in highly repetitive regions where reads would often be wrongly mapped
anyway.

.SH THE INDEX COMMAND
.SS Summary
.B minibwa index
.RB [ -l ]
.RB [ -t
.IR nThreads ]
.I ref.fa
.I idxPrefix

Index a genome in the FASTA format. Generate
.IR idxPrefix .l2b
for the genome sequence and
.IR idxPrefix .mbw
for the FM-index. Minibwa uses the libsais algorithm for BWT construction by
default. This algorithm is fast but requires
.RI 18 N
bytes where
.I N
is the length of the genome. Use
.B -l
to enable the BWT-SW algorithm which is slower but uses much less memory.

.SS Options
.TP 10
.B -l
Use the old low-memory algorithm for BWT construction. Minibwa uses the libsais
algorithm by default which uses over 50 GB for a human genome.
.TP
.BI -t \ INT
Number of threads for the libsais algorithm [1]. Minibwa needs to be compiled
with OpenMP to enable this option.

.SH THE MAP COMMAND
.SS Summary
.B minibwa map
.RB [ -a ]
.RB [ -x
.IR preset ]
.RB [ -t
.IR nThreads ]
.I idxPrefix
.I read.fq.gz
.RI [ read2.fq.gz ]

Map reads to an index genome. By default, minibwa assumes short-read input and
outputs alignment in the PAF format. Use
.B -a
for SAM output and preset
.B -x lr
for long-read alignment. In the short-read mode, minibwa automatically detects
interleaved read pairs and like bwa-mem and minimap2, allowing mixed single-end
and paired-ened reads as input.

.SS Common options
.TP 10
.B -a
Output alignment in the SAM format (PAF by default)
.TP
.BI -t \ INT
Number of worker CPU threads [1]
.TP
.BI -x \ STR
Preset:
.BR sr ,
.B lr
or
.B adap
.RB [ adap ]
.RS
.TP 6
.B sr
For short-read alignment. It may give fragmented alignment for typical long reads.
.TP
.B lr
For long-read alignment. It may miss highly repetitive alignments for typical short reads.
.TP
.B adap
For mixed short and long reads but optimized for short reads. It is equivalent to
.RB ' -xsr
.BR --adap=yes '.
This mode adjusts several parameters based on the read length, asymptotically
reaching the long-read setting. It enables additional long-read heuristic (mapQ
formula and anchor filtering) if reads is longer than option
.BR -l .
.RE
.TP
.BI -l \ NUM
In the adaptive mode, treat reads shorter than
.I NUM
as short reads [325]
.TP
.BI -R \ STR
SAM read group line in a format like '@RG\\tID:foo\\tSM:bar' []
.TP
.BI -b \ STR
Output a base alignment tag:
.BR cs,
.B ds
or
.B MD
[]. Only one tag is allowed.

.SS Mapping options
.TP 10
.BI -k \ INT
Minimum seed length [19]. Like bwa-mem, minibwa uses variable-length seeds.
.TP
.BI -c \ NUM
Maximum seed occurrence [250]. Minibwa samples up to
.I NUM
occurrences if there are too many.
.TP
.BI -m \ INT
Minimum chaining score [25]
.TP
.BI -p \ FLOAT
Minimum secondary-to-primary score ratio [0.5]
.TP
.BI -N \ INT
Retain at most
.I INT
secondary alignments [101]
.TP
.BR --adap = yes | no
Enable/disable adaptive mode. Enabled with the default
.B adap
preset.
.TP
.B --chain-only
Perform chaining only without base alignment

.SS Alignment options
.TP 10
.BI -A \ INT
Match score [2]
.TP
.BI -B \ INT
Mismatch penalty [8]
.TP
.B -O \fIINT1\fR[,\fIINT2\fR]
Dual gap open penalty [12,23]. If
.I INT2
is not specified, it is set to
.IR INT1 .
.TP
.B -E \fIINT1\fR[,\fIINT2\fR]
Dual gap extension penalty [2,1]. If
.I INT2
is not specified, it is set to
.IR INT1 .
A gap of length
.I k
costs
.RI min{ O1 + k * E1 , O2 + k * E2 }.

.SH OUTPUT FORMATS
.PP
Minibwa outputs the PAF format by default. It is a TAB-delimited text format
with each line consisting of at least 12 fields as are described in the
following table:
.TS
center box;
cb | cb | cb
r | c | l .
Col	Type	Description
_
1	string	Read name
2	int	Read length
3	int	Read start coordinate (0-based)
4	int	Read end coordinate (0-based)
5	char	`+' for forward strand; `-' for reverse
6	string	Contig name
7	int	Contig length
8	int	Contig start coordinate on the original strand
9	int	Contig end coordinate on the original strand
10	int	Number of matching bases
11	int	Number of bases in alignment
12	int	Mapping quality (0-255 with 255 for missing)
.TE

.PP
Option
.B -a
enables the SAM output. Both SAM and PAF may have addtional fields in typed
key-value format. Minibwa may output the following tags:
.TS
center box;
cb | cb | cb
r | c | l .
Tag	Type	Description
_
AS	i	Alignment score from dynamic programming
ms	i	Score of the maximum scoring segment
cg	Z	CIGAR (PAF only)
MD	Z	Difference string in the SAM spec
cs	Z	Difference string
.TE

.SH LIMITATIONS
.TP 2
*
Minibwa does not work noisy long reads.
.TP
*
In the default adaptive mode, minibwa does not
.I smoothly
transition between short- and long-read modes.
